title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare LNIB Smith & Wesson Model 916T Field Grade 12 ga Pump Shotgun
postcontent:
.
Smith & Wesson Model 916T Field Grade 12 ga Pump Shotgun LNIB


The only S&W shotgun that was ever MADE IN USA. Not all 916T's were created equal. This one is a rare version of the 916T that has:

- Wildlife Scene (Duck in flight with Catails) Engraved in the Receiver
- Checkering in the Forearm and Grip
- White Line Spacers at the Recoil Pad and Pistol Grip Cap 
- Two-Bead Wavy Top Ventilated Rib.
- Correct O stamp Barrel (NO Recall) with Chrome Bore

This is the barrel that shipped with the gun, not a S&W recall replacement barrel, so the gun must have been a very late one with the revisions already in place. The barrel is 28" and Steel Shot Safe.


In all the years I have owned the gun I have never seen another one like it (I saw 'one' that was similar but did not have the correct barrel). Every other 916T I have seen was the plain jane version with no engraving, no checkering, no spacer's, if they had a VR at all it was a standard one, and all, but a handful, did not have the correct O stamped barrel which can be dangerous.


Barrel Markings on Left Side:

SMITH & WESSON - MODEL 916T
SPRINGFIELD, MA., - MADE IN U.S.A.

Right Side:

PROOF TESTED 12 GA.
- 3 INCH CHAMBER -
MODIFIED CHOKE


I bought the gun brand new many years ago. Fired 50~100 rounds. I have the original box, but cannot find the paperwork.


Please no message's quoting book value as this gun is simply not in the book with the feature's that it has. The book lists only the plain jane 916T with a potentially dangerous barrel. Even so, I am pricing this Deluxe 916T right in line with the book value of the plain jane 916T. Condition is an easy 98% or Excellent, depending on the book.


$250 firm or Trade up/down/even for Wood Field/Sporting/Hunting Long Guns, a .22 Auto Target Pistol, or a Large Caliber Revolver with 5" plus barrel for deer hunting. Can add cash.

May also trade for 28 squares of shingles, a truck stake bed (bed/rails only), motorcycle, lawn tractor, Gibson, Epihone or EPS electric guitar, vintage minibike, ?

title: For Sale:  Colt Commando .38 Special
postcontent:
Have for sale out right $375 (obo) a Colt Commando Spec. Read history below. This piece is in really good condition for it's age. Photos show some wear, but there are no scratches or gouges. This piece was well cared for. It has a six round cylinder which locks up tight. I believe this is dated at about 1984, serial number begins with letter "P".

I live in Little Rock, but am willing to meet half way of where you're at. You can own a part of history for the right price!!!!

Additional photos can be seen at: http://s398.photobucket.com/albums/pp67/tawcat/Colt%20Commando%20Spec/

A Little History

The Commando Special was a limited time offering from Colt.

During the big Colt strike of the mid-1980's, Colt didn't have enough polishers still working to do the amount of work needed.

So, they introduced a series of Colt revolvers with unpolished black finishes, and had the available polishers concentrate on the premium guns like the Python, and the easier to polish 1911 autos.

These were nothing more than standard guns, only unpolished and with flat black parkerized finishes.

There was a "Peacekeeper" which was an unpolished Trooper Mark V, an unpolished Detective Special known as the "Commando Special" and an unpolished Cobra and Agent.

For unknown reasons, Colt didn't assign special names to the unpolished Agent and Cobra versions.

The Commando Special was only made from 1984 to 1986.

The buying public didn't care for these unpolished guns, so as soon as the strike ended they were dropped.

Internally, the guns were the same quality as the polished guns.

title: For Sale:  Ugly, rough, rusty, 1962 Belgium Browning SA-22 Take-down... FUGLY!!
postcontent:
This 1962 Belgium Browning is the real deal and it show.  It is very ugly with a lot of rust, pits, no blueing to speak of.  Any wood on this is cracked wood. This certainly is not that nice Patina that collectors desire, it is ugly rust that you may die from touching.  
I cannot imagine there is another person on the planet, like myself, that would actually want to own this gun.  Prior to handling this Browning you may consider getting a Tetanus shot. It doesn't even smell that great.  I understand this sat in the back of a pick-up for several years.  Initially I thought that meant behind the seat, but for all I know it looks like it sat in the truck bed.  I cannot believe the bolt even opens.  One thing that throws me off is the rod that comes out of the stock, it still looks good for some reason, which is why I hate that "uppity" part of the rifle.  And the rifling in the bore... don't get me started.  I wanted to pour some rust growth down the nearly perfect barrel just so it would match the outside.  Despicable how clean the bore is to how ugly the rest of the rifle is.  
Most of the checkering on the furniture has been rubbed off.  The hole in the stock where you stick it in is also in good condition for being a hole that is 49 years old!  If there ever was a Browning trademark on the trigger guard, it has been replaced by a bunch of rust.  The rear sight looks like it has seen better days, and the front sight looks like cancer is starting to take it over.  
Currently, it's best performing trick is coming apart into two pieces.  It still does this well.
I usually don't post my entire serial number of a gun for the public to see, but what is the worst you are going to do?  Call Browning and make a warranty claim using my 49 year old serial number? 
SN:2T41417 ... Yes, that is correct, the end of this serial number is THIS AREA CODE!!!  (417) BABY!!!  
What's that?  Have I shot it?  Nope, I have not even tried.  I am concerned some of the rust will come off, and may even embed itself in my skin.  Being a Belgium Browning, this damn thing will probably still fire 49 years later even if it is as rough as Charlie Sheen on 1/2 price p0rn star night.  
How much?  Too much.  $475 and you are welcome to send me hate emails telling me how you bought one for $75 back in 1901 at Sears and they served you with a smile.  Awesome for you, mine is $475.  
They quite making this Belgium Browning in 1974, so all that are ever going to be produced were done 37 years ago.  I think this WAS considered a "Grade 1" but now it is "Rusty Rifle #1".
If you made it this far, you have as much time on your hand as I do.  Blame it on Sarah Palin and Obama is 1/2 white.

title: For Sale:  NIB Kel-Tec P3AT in Custom Brown Billfold color
postcontent:
P-3AT (Custom Billfold Brown Color)
The P-3AT is a semi-automatic, locked breech pistol, chambered for the .380 Auto cartridge. It has been developed from our highly successful P-32 pistol with negligible increase in weight and size. The slidestop has been eliminated and the magazine capacity reduced to 6 rounds due to the larger cartridge. The firing mechanism is double action only. The magazine has a 6 round capacity. The KEL-TEC P-3AT is the lightest .380 Auto pistol ever made. Thanks to its locking dynamics and superior ergonometry, perceived recoil and practical accuracy are comparable to much larger guns. The P-3AT is mainly intended for plainclothes police officers as a secondary weapon, or for concealed carry by licensed citizens. The small grip size and light trigger pull make the P-3AT ideal for female shooters.

TECHNICAL SPECIFICATIONS
Calibers:	.380 AUTO
Weight unloaded:	8.3 oz.	235g
Loaded magazine:	2.8 oz.	81g
Length:	5.2"	132mm
Height:	3.5"	89mm
Width:	.77"	20mm
Barrel Length:	2.7"	68mm
Sight radius:	3.8"	97mm
Muzzle Energy Max:	250ft-lbs	340J
Capacity:	6 + 1 rounds
Trigger Pull:	5 lbs	23N

The P-3AT has five main component groups: barrel, slide, firing mechanism, grip, and magazine. The barrel is made of SAE 4140 ordnance steel, heat treated to 48 HRC. The slide is also 4140 steel, and contains the firing pin and the extractor. The rectangular frame is machined from solid 7075-T6 aluminum and houses the firing mechanism. The trigger connects via a transfer bar to the hammer. The hammer is driven by a novel free floating extension spring. The light weight firing pin transmits the energy of the hammer to ignite the primer. After firing, the hammer block holds the hammer away from the firing pin, providing a mechanical safety.
